## ‚úÖ Incident Summary

**Root Cause:** The `orders` table (500M rows) had only a primary key index on `id`. All other columns ‚Äî `user_id`, `order_date`, `status`, `amount` ‚Äî were completely unindexed, forcing every business query into a full sequential scan of half a billion rows.

**Fix Applied:** Three B-Tree indexes created using `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` (per `docs/index_guide.md`):

| Index | Column | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | User order lookups |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Date range queries, reporting |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Order status filtering |

**Safety:** Every index was built with `CONCURRENTLY` ‚Äî only a `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` was held (non-blocking). Writes continued uninterrupted throughout. Zero downtime, zero write contention.

**Expected outcome:** Queries filtering on these columns will now use index scans instead of sequential scans, dropping response times from 10+ seconds to milliseconds for the vast majority of slow queries.

**Rollback plan** (if needed): `DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_user_id;` etc. ‚Äî also non-blocking.
